{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:148","names":{"en":"Safavid","tr":"Safevîler","ar":"al-Safawiyyūn"},"country":["AF","AZ","GE","IQ","IR","MN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1501,"extinct":1736},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"148","atlas_name_en_original":"The Safavids","parent_tribe":"Safevî tarikatı (Erdebil)","ethnic_origin":"Türk-İranî (Azerbaycanlı/Kürt kökenli tartışmalı)","capital":"Tebriz → Kazvin → İsfahan","region_primary":"İran","regions_all":"Tebriz; Kazvin; İsfahan; Azerbaycan; Horasan; Irak (geçici); Gürcistan; Herat (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Moğol/Tatar Dünyası","predecessor":"Akkoyunlular; Timurlular (Horasan)","successor":"Afşarlar (Nâdir Şah)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Safavids were the dynasty that transformed Iran into a Twelver Shī'ī state, laying the foundations of modern Iranian national identity. Founded through Shāh Ismā'īl's charismatic leadership, the state transformed Isfahan into one of the world's most magnificent capitals under Shāh Abbās. While Ottoman-Safavid rivalry permanently shaped the Sunni-Shī'ī axis of the Middle East, Isfahan's Naqsh-e Jahān Square was built as one of Islamic architecture's most spectacular plazas. The Safavids also institutionalized the Iranian carpet tradition, miniature painting, and Shī'ī theology. The dynasty, which collapsed when the Afghan Ghilzai invasion took Isfahan, permanently determined Iran's political structure.","importance_level":"Kritik","capital_lat":"32.65","capital_lon":"51.68","century_start":16,"century_end":18}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:77","names":{"en":"'Annāzid","tr":"Annâzîler","ar":"al-'Annāziyyūn"},"country":["AM","AZ","GE","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"77","atlas_name_en_original":"The 'Annāzids","parent_tribe":"Şâzencân Kürt aşireti","ethnic_origin":"Kürt","capital":"Hulvân","region_primary":"Cibâl (Hulvân-Dînevar)","regions_all":"Hulvân; Dînevar; Şâhrizor (geçici); Dakkûkā","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Hasanveyhîler (kısmen)","successor":"Selçuklu nüfuzu","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The 'Annāzids were a Kurdish principality ruling in a strategic position near the Iraqi border along the Hulwan-Dinavar axis. Reaching their peak under Abū al-Fatḥ Muḥammad's leadership, this dynasty played a role in regional balances during the Būyid-Seljuq transition period.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"34.35","capital_lon":"45.58","century_start":10,"century_end":12}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:80","names":{"en":"Bāwandid Ispahbadh","tr":"Bâvendî İspehbedleri","ar":"al-Bāwandiyyūn"},"country":["AM","AZ","GE","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"80","atlas_name_en_original":"The Bāwandid Ispahbadhs","parent_tribe":"Bâvend ailesi (Sâsânî soyundan iddia)","ethnic_origin":"İranî (Taberistân)","capital":"Firrim (1. kol); Sârî (2. kol); Amul (3. kol)","region_primary":"Taberistân","regions_all":"Taberistân; Gîlân (kısmen); Firrim; Sârî; Amul","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Sâsânî yerel beyleri","successor":"Timurlu fethi","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Bāwandid Ispahbadhs ruled in Tabaristan for nearly seven centuries, forming one of the Islamic world's longest-lasting dynasties alongside the Shirvanshahs. Governing in three separate branches, the Bāwandids successfully carried the Sasanian Ispahbadh tradition into the Islamic era.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"36.56","capital_lon":"53.06","century_start":7,"century_end":14}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:79","names":{"en":"Dābūyid Ispahbadh","tr":"Dâbûyî İspehbedleri","ar":"al-Dābūyiyyūn"},"country":["AM","AZ","GE","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"79","atlas_name_en_original":"The Dābūyid Ispahbadhs","parent_tribe":"Dâbûye ailesi (yerel İranî soy)","ethnic_origin":"İranî (Taberistân)","capital":null,"region_primary":"Taberistân (Hazar Denizi güney kıyısı)","regions_all":"Taberistân; Amul; Sârî","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Sâsânî yerel beyleri","successor":"Bâvendîler; Abbâsî valileri","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Dābūyids were a dynasty continuing the Iranian Ispahbadh tradition from the Sasanian era in the mountainous Tabaristan region. As one of the last Iranian principalities resisting Islam, they ended with the Abbasid army's conquest of the region.","importance_level":"Düşük","capital_lat":"36.56","capital_lon":"53.06","century_start":7,"century_end":8}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:68","names":{"en":"Hāshimid","tr":"Hâşimîler (Derbent)","ar":"al-Hāshimiyyūn"},"country":["AM","AZ","GE","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"68","atlas_name_en_original":"The Hāshimids","parent_tribe":"Hâşimî (Sülemî kolu)","ethnic_origin":"Arap","capital":"Derbent (Bāb al-Abwāb)","region_primary":"Derbent (Bâbülabvâb)","regions_all":"Derbent; Kuzey Kafkasya sınır bölgesi","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Abbâsî sınır valileri","successor":"Selçuklu nüfuzu","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Hāshimids of Derbent governed Bāb al-Abwāb ('Gate of Gates'), the most strategic pass in the Caucasus, for two centuries, serving as a critical frontier fortress in Islam's northward expansion. Transitioning from Abbasid border governorship to a local dynasty, they defended the Islamic frontier against Khazar and Caucasian peoples.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"42.06","capital_lon":"48.3","century_start":9,"century_end":11}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:69","names":{"en":"Justānid","tr":"Cüstânîler","ar":"al-Jūstāniyyūn"},"country":["AM","AZ","GE","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"69","atlas_name_en_original":"The Justānids","parent_tribe":"Cüstân ailesi (yerel Deylemi)","ethnic_origin":"İranî (Deylemi)","capital":null,"region_primary":"Deylem (Hazar Denizi güney kıyısı)","regions_all":"Deylem; Gîlân kısmen","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Yerel Deylemi kabile beyleri","successor":"Büveyhî/Selçuklu nüfuzu","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Justānids were a local Iranian dynasty governing the late-Islamizing communities in the mountainous Daylam region on the southern shore of the Caspian Sea. Facilitating Islam's penetration into this region, the Justānids can be considered precursors to the Būyids who emerged from the same geography.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"37.5","capital_lon":"49.5","century_start":8,"century_end":11}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:78","names":{"en":"Kākūyid","tr":"Kâkûyîler (Kâkaveyhîler)","ar":"al-Kākūyiyyūn"},"country":["AM","AZ","GE","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"78","atlas_name_en_original":"The Kākūyids or Kākawayhids","parent_tribe":"Deylemi ailesi","ethnic_origin":"İranî (Deylemi)","capital":"İsfahan; Yezd (geç dönem)","region_primary":"Cibâl (İsfahan, Hemedân)","regions_all":"İsfahan; Hemedân; Cibâl; Yezd (geç dönem)","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Büveyhîler","successor":"Selçuklu doğrudan yönetimi","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Kākūyids were a dynasty of Daylamī origin that rose in Isfahan and Hamadan as the Būyids weakened. Under 'Alā' al-Dawla's leadership, resisting both Ghaznavid Mahmud and Seljuq Tughril Beg, the Kākūyids continued as a small principality in Yazd after being expelled from Isfahan.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"32.65","capital_lon":"51.68","century_start":11,"century_end":12}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:70","names":{"en":"Sajid","tr":"Sâcîler (Sâcoğulları)","ar":"al-Sājiyyūn"},"country":["AM","AZ","IR","TR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":879,"extinct":930},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"70","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sajids","parent_tribe":"Sâc ailesi (Uşrûsana Türk/İranî)","ethnic_origin":"Türk/İranî (Uşrûsana)","capital":"Merâga; Erdebîl","region_primary":"Azerbaycan ve Ermenistan","regions_all":"Azerbaycan; Ermenistan; Diyâr-ı Bekr (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Abbâsî valileri","successor":"Müsâfirîler/Sellarîler","government_type":"Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Sajids, a Turco-Iranian family from Ushrusana, rose through Abbasid service to become a significant regional power controlling Azerbaijan and Armenia. Despite their short lifespan, they represented one of the earliest examples of Turco-Islamic presence in the Caucasus. Yūsuf b. Abū al-Sāj, the dynasty's most powerful emir, played a decisive role in Abbasid politics.","importance_level":"Yüksek","capital_lat":"37.39","capital_lon":"46.22","century_start":9,"century_end":10}}
