{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:133","names":{"en":"Il Khānids (descendants of Hülegü)","tr":"İlhanlılar","ar":"al-Īlkhāniyyūn"},"country":["AZ","GE","IQ","IR","TR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1256,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"133","atlas_name_en_original":"The Il Khānids (descendants of Hülegü)","parent_tribe":"Borcigin (Toluy → Hülâgü kolu)","ethnic_origin":"Moğol → İslamlaşmış","capital":"Merâga → Tebriz → Sultaniye","region_primary":"İran, Irak, Azerbaycan, Anadolu (kısmen)","regions_all":"Tebriz; Sultaniye; İsfahan; Bağdat; Azerbaycan; Anadolu (tâbi); Gürcistan; Horasan","geographic_zone":"Irak/Cezîre","predecessor":"Hârezmşahlar; Abbâsîler (Bağdat); çeşitli İran hanedanları","successor":"Celâyirliler; Muzafferîler; Kurtlar; çeşitli yerel hanedanlar","government_type":"Hanlık","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Il-Khanids were a Mongol state centered on Iran-Iraq-Azerbaijan founded by Hülegü. Having ended the Abbasid caliphate by destroying Baghdad, the Il-Khanids underwent transformation with Ghāzān Khān's conversion to Islam. Under Öljeitü, they left magnificent architectural works in Sultaniyya, creating the most brilliant example of the Mongol-Islamic synthesis.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"38.08","capital_lon":"46.29","century_start":13,"century_end":14}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:142","names":{"en":"Jalayirid","tr":"Celâyirliler","ar":"al-Jalā'iriyyūn"},"country":["AZ","IQ","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"142","atlas_name_en_original":"The Jalayirids","parent_tribe":"Celâyir Moğol kabilesi","ethnic_origin":"Moğol → Türkleşmiş","capital":"Bağdat; Tebriz","region_primary":"Irak ve Azerbaycan","regions_all":"Bağdat; Tebriz; Sultaniye; Basra","geographic_zone":"Irak/Cezîre","predecessor":"İlhanlı çöküşü","successor":"Karakoyunlu/Timurlu","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Jalayirids were a Mongol-Turkic dynasty that rose centered on Baghdad and Tabriz after the Il-Khanid collapse. Sultan Ahmad Jalayir created a rare artist-ruler figure in Islamic art history as both a calligrapher and painter. Severely damaged by Timur's repeated campaigns, the dynasty was liquidated by the Qara Qoyunlu.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"33.31","capital_lon":"44.37","century_start":14,"century_end":15}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:145","names":{"en":"Qara Qoyunlu","tr":"Karakoyunlular","ar":"Qara Qōyunlū"},"country":["AZ","IQ","IR","TR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1469},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"145","atlas_name_en_original":"The Qara Qoyunlu","parent_tribe":"Karakoyunlu Türkmen konfederasyonu","ethnic_origin":"Türk (Oğuz/Türkmen)","capital":"Tebriz","region_primary":"Azerbaycan ve Doğu Anadolu","regions_all":"Tebriz; Van; Erzincan; Bağdat (geçici); Fars (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Celâyirliler / İlhanlı artıkları","successor":"Akkoyunlu Uzun Hasan fethi (874/1469)","government_type":"Şahlık","religious_orientation":"Şiî","narrative_en":"The Qara Qoyunlu were a Shī'ī-leaning Turkmen confederation ruling in eastern Anatolia and Azerbaijan. A culturally brilliant period occurred under the poet-ruler Jahānshāh (pen name Ḥaqīqī). They were destroyed by Āq Qoyunlu Uzun Hasan.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"38.08","capital_lon":"46.29","century_start":14,"century_end":15}}
