{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:99","names":{"en":"Eldigüzid","tr":"İldenizliler (Eldigüzlüler)","ar":"al-Ildikiziyyūn"},"country":["AZ","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1137,"extinct":1225},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"99","atlas_name_en_original":"The Eldigüzids or Ildegizids","parent_tribe":"Türk (Kıpçak kökenli gulâm)","ethnic_origin":"Türk (Kıpçak)","capital":"Tebriz; Nahçıvan; Hemedân","region_primary":"Azerbaycan ve Errân","regions_all":"Azerbaycan; Tebriz; Hemedân; Errân (Gence); Nahçıvan; İsfahan (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Selçuklu Irak Sultanlığı (vasalı)","successor":"Hârezmşah fethi (622/1225)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Eldigüzids, founded by a commander of Qipchaq Turkic slave origin and known as the Atabegs of Azerbaijan, seized effective control of the Iraq Seljuqs and defended the Islamic frontier against the Georgians. They remained the region's most powerful political actor until the Khwārazm Shāh Jalāl al-Dīn's conquests.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"38.08","capital_lon":"46.29","century_start":12,"century_end":13}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:71","names":{"en":"Musāfirid","tr":"Müsâfirîler (Sellârîler)","ar":"al-Musāfiriyyūn / al-Sallāriyyūn"},"country":["AZ","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"71","atlas_name_en_original":"The Musāfirids or Sallārids","parent_tribe":"Deylemi askerî ailesi","ethnic_origin":"İranî (Deylemi)","capital":"Tebriz; Erdebîl","region_primary":"Azerbaycan ve Deylem","regions_all":"Azerbaycan (Tebriz, Erdebîl); Deylem","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Sâcîler","successor":"Selçuklu nüfuzu / Ravvâdîler","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Musāfirids were an Iranian dynasty that established strong regional dominance in Azerbaijan through the Daylamī military tradition. Governing in two branches, the Musāfirids experienced their peak under Marzubān b. Muhammad's leadership. Carrying the Daylamī warrior culture into Azerbaijani politics, this dynasty shaped the power dynamics of the 10th-century Caucasus.","importance_level":"Yüksek","capital_lat":"38.08","capital_lon":"46.29","century_start":10,"century_end":11}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:72","names":{"en":"Rawwādid","tr":"Ravvâdîler","ar":"al-Rawwādiyyūn"},"country":["AZ","IR"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"72","atlas_name_en_original":"The Rawwādids","parent_tribe":"Ezdî Arap kabilesi (Ravvâd b. Müsennâ)","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Ezdî) → Kürtleşmiş","capital":"Tebriz","region_primary":"Azerbaycan (Tebriz)","regions_all":"Tebriz; Azerbaycan","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Sâcîler / Müsâfirîler","successor":"Selçuklu fethi","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Rawwādids, despite their Azdī Arab origins, gradually became Kurdicized and created a distinctive cultural identity centered on Tabriz, Azerbaijan's most important city. Reaching their peak under Abū al-Hayjā' Ḥusayn, the Rawwādids contributed to Tabriz's historical trajectory toward becoming Azerbaijan's capital.","importance_level":"Yüksek","capital_lat":"38.08","capital_lon":"46.29","century_start":10,"century_end":11}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:67","names":{"en":"Sharwān Shāh","tr":"Şirvanşahlar","ar":"Shīrwān Shāhiyyūn"},"country":["AZ","IR","SY"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"67","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sharwān Shāhs","parent_tribe":"1. Yezîdî Şahlar (Arap kökenli iddia); 2. İkinci Şah soyu","ethnic_origin":"Arap (iddia) / İranî","capital":"Şamahı (Shamākhī); Bakü (geç dönem)","region_primary":"Şirvan (Doğu Kafkasya / Azerbaycan)","regions_all":"Şirvan; Bakü; Şamahı; Derbent (geçici)","geographic_zone":"Kafkasya/Batı İran","predecessor":"Sâsânî sınır valileri","successor":"Safevî fethi","government_type":"Şahlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Sharwān Shāhs ruled for nearly eight centuries in the Eastern Caucasus, forming one of the Islamic world's longest-lasting dynasties. Transforming from Sasanian border governorship to an Islamic principality, the dynasty left an architectural and cultural legacy in the Shirvan region. The Palace of the Shirvanshahs in Baku remains the most visible evidence of this tradition.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"33.51","capital_lon":"36.29","century_start":8,"century_end":16}}
